<subSubSection id="35E7653C5734B240FF0F69C8FE9667B1" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="280" pageId="6" pageNumber="279" type="description">
<paragraph id="7D4236B75734B241FF0F69C8FD866623" blockId="6.[151,1127,586,1601]" pageId="6" pageNumber="279">
<emphasis id="4F89EAA55734B241FF0F69C8FEA167A3" bold="true" box="[151,361,681,705]" pageId="6" pageNumber="279">
Description. 
<emphasis id="4F89EAA55734B241FEB269CBFEA167A3" bold="true" box="[298,361,681,705]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="279">Male.</emphasis>
</emphasis>
Colouration (
<figureCitation id="E5C62A325734B241FD9969C8FDAC67A3" box="[513,612,682,705]" captionStart="Figs 1–5" captionStartId="10.[151,188,1518,1537]" captionTargetBox="[169,1121,231,1466]" captionTargetId="figure-10@10.[151,1129,219,1472]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 1–5. Male habitus: 1 – Oulema duftschmidi (Retdenbacher, 1874) (4.6 mm); 2 – O. melanopus (Linnaeus, 1758) (4.5 mm); 3 – O. rufocyanea (Suffrian, 1847) (4.2 mm); 4 – O. mauroi sp. nov., holotype (4.4 mm); 5 – O. verae sp. nov., holotype (4.0mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5303693" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5303693/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="279">Figs 1–5</figureCitation>
). Head dark metallic blue, antennae black with antennomeres I and II dark metallic blue. Pronotum orange-red, anterior and posterior margins sometimes thinly black. Scutellum and elytra metallic blue to black. Meso-, metathorax and abdominal ventrites metallic blue to metallic black. Legs: coxae, trochanters, tarsi and apices of tibiae black, femora and tibiae orange.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7D4236B75734B241FF2D6828FD0E6603" blockId="6.[151,1127,586,1601]" box="[181,710,842,865]" pageId="6" pageNumber="279">Body moderately flat, parallel, glabrous, lustrous.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7D4236B75734B241FF2D6808FE946143" blockId="6.[151,1127,586,1601]" pageId="6" pageNumber="279">
Head. Frontoclypeus triangular, punctate and covered with setae, anterior margin more or less straight; frontal tubercles not elevated, smooth, glabrous; frontal grooves very deep, V-shaped, frons covered with large punctures, each bearing long pale seta; vertex covered with small punctures, almost glabrous, with distinct median line. Antennae slender, 0.45–0.61 times as long as body, antennomere I bulbous, antennomere II smallest, almost as wide as long (
<figureCitation id="E5C62A325734B241FF4D6F68FE986143" box="[213,336,1034,1057]" captionStart="Figs 6–15" captionStartId="11.[113,149,1513,1532]" captionTargetBox="[150,1063,225,1469]" captionTargetId="figure-16@11.[122,1081,209,1490]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs 6–15. Male pronotum:6 – Oulema duftschmidi (Redtenbacher, 1874); 7 – O. melanopus (Linnaeus, 1758); 8 – O. rufocyanea (Suffrian, 1847); 9 – O. mauroi sp. nov.; 10 – O. verae sp. nov. Left male antenna: 11 – O. duftschmidi; 12 – O. melanopus; 13 – O. rufocyanea; 14 – O. mauroi sp. nov.; 15 – O. verae sp. nov.." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5303695" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5303695/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="279">Figs 11–15</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7D4236B75734B241FF2D6F48FB8F6063" blockId="6.[151,1127,586,1601]" pageId="6" pageNumber="279">
Pronotum quadratic or subquadratic (
<figureCitation id="E5C62A325734B241FDDB6F48FD7A6123" box="[579,690,1066,1089]" captionStart="Figs 6–15" captionStartId="11.[113,149,1513,1532]" captionTargetBox="[150,1063,225,1469]" captionTargetId="figure-16@11.[122,1081,209,1490]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs 6–15. Male pronotum:6 – Oulema duftschmidi (Redtenbacher, 1874); 7 – O. melanopus (Linnaeus, 1758); 8 – O. rufocyanea (Suffrian, 1847); 9 – O. mauroi sp. nov.; 10 – O. verae sp. nov. Left male antenna: 11 – O. duftschmidi; 12 – O. melanopus; 13 – O. rufocyanea; 14 – O. mauroi sp. nov.; 15 – O. verae sp. nov.." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5303695" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5303695/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="279">Figs 6–10</figureCitation>
), widest at midlength or just before midlength, convex, lustrous. Surface shallowly constricted before base. Disc covered with sparse large punctures, basal constriction and area around posterior corners usually covered with very small dense punctures. Anterior margin thinly bordered, lateral margins almost parallel to widely rounded, unbordered, in posterior half always convergent, posterior margin slightly rounded, thinly bordered. Anterior angles more or less rectangular with swollen tip, posterior ones only slightly indicated. All angles bearing setigerous pore with erect long pale seta.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7D4236B75734B241FF2D6E68FBC66023" blockId="6.[151,1127,586,1601]" pageId="6" pageNumber="279">Scutellum trapezoidal, ca. as wide as long, lateral margins slightly convergent, posterior margin slightly concave, straight or slightly rounded, surface glabrous, impunctate.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7D4236B75734B241FF2D6E28FC226083" blockId="6.[151,1127,586,1601]" pageId="6" pageNumber="279">Elytra moderately flat, 1.69–2.05 times as long as wide at humeral part, glabrous, lustrous, covered with 10 striae composed of large deep punctures (smaller and shallower near basal margin and in apical area) and short scutellar stria composed of 4–6 small shallow punctures; distance between punctures on elytral disc ca. as wide as diameter of puncture. Humeral calli well developed, impunctate. Epipleura very narrow, disappearing towards apex.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7D4236B75734B241FF2D6E88FC866323" blockId="6.[151,1127,586,1601]" pageId="6" pageNumber="279">Legs. Femora lustrous, moderately covered with pale setae. Tibiae slender, slightly tapering basally, covered with dense pubescence, outer side on basal half nearly glabrous, apices armed with pair of short, subequal, black-brown spines ventrally.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7D4236B75735B240FF086BBEFD2C6471" blockId="7.[113,1089,220,1011]" pageId="7" pageNumber="280">Tarsi relatively slender. Tarsomeres I elongate triangular, shorter than two following tarsomeres combined, tarsomeres II triangular. Claws simple.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7D4236B75735B240FF086A7EFEB16771" blockId="7.[113,1089,220,1011]" pageId="7" pageNumber="280">Ventral part. Prosternal projection not visible between procoxae. Mesoventrite densely covered with small punctures bearing pale setae, mesoventral process wide, separating mesocoxae, ca. 0.5 times as wide as diameter of mesocoxa. Metaventrite laterally and anteriorly subopaque, covered with large punctures bearing pale setae; medially and towards posterior margin lustrous, nearly impunctate; medially at posterior quarter with impressed line; posterior margin shallowly incised in middle. Abdominal ventrites lustrous, uniformly covered with small punctures bearing pale setae; ventrite I twice as long as II and III combined, ventrite V 1.5 time as long as IV.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7D4236B75735B240FF08697EFD386731" blockId="7.[113,1089,220,1011]" pageId="7" pageNumber="280">
Male genitalia. Aedeagus of relatively uniform structure, but with specific internal sclerite (flagellum) posessing short posterobasal arms (
<figureCitation id="E5C62A325735B240FDFF695EFD2B6731" box="[615,739,572,595]" captionStart="Figs 16–23" captionStartId="12.[151,188,1515,1534]" captionTargetBox="[183,1046,236,1363]" captionTargetId="figure-10@12.[151,1129,230,1371]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 16–23. Flagellum of aedeagus in lateral (upper) and dorsal (below) view: 16 – Oulema duftschmidi (Redtenbacher, 1874); 17 – O. melanopus (Linnaeus, 1758) (Czech Republic); 18 – O. melanopus (Suffrian, 1847) (Spain); 19 – O. rufocyanea (Slovakia); 20 – O. rufocyanea (Hungary); 21 –O. rufocyanea (Italy); 22 – O. mauroi sp. nov.; 23 – O. verae sp. nov. Scale bar: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5303697" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5303697/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="280">Figs 16–23</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7D4236B75735B240FF086939FE9667B1" blockId="7.[113,1089,220,1011]" pageId="7" pageNumber="280">
<emphasis id="4F89EAA55735B240FF086939FF216711" bold="true" box="[144,233,603,627]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="280">Female.</emphasis>
Sexual dimorphism indistinct. Females have usually more convex abdomen. Spermatheca with duct heavily sclerotized in proximal part, soft in shorter basal part, with specific junction to bursa copulatrix (
<figureCitation id="E5C62A325735B240FD8969FEFD5A67D1" box="[529,658,668,691]" captionStart="Figs 26–30" captionStartId="21.[113,150,1159,1178]" captionTargetBox="[182,1035,223,1143]" captionTargetId="figure-16@21.[160,1043,219,1147]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figs 26–30. Spermatheca and ductus spermathecae: 26 – Oulema duftschmidi (Redtenbacher, 1874); 27 – O. melanopus (Linnaeus, 1758); 28 – O. rufocyanea (Suffrian, 1847); 29 – O. mauroi sp. nov.; 30 – O. verae sp. nov. Scale bar: 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5303701" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5303701/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="280">Figs 26–30</figureCitation>
). Nodulus poorly developed, gradually connected with cornu.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="35E7653C5735B240FFE969BEFCCB66D1" pageId="7" pageNumber="280" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="7D4236B75735B240FFE969BEFCCB66D1" blockId="7.[113,1089,220,1011]" pageId="7" pageNumber="280">
<emphasis id="4F89EAA55735B240FFE969BEFF3F6791" bold="true" box="[113,247,732,755]" pageId="7" pageNumber="280">Host plants.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="BAFD4D345735B240FF6369BEFE076791" baseAuthorityName="Redtenbacher" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[251,463,732,755]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Oulema" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="duftschmidi">
<emphasis id="4F89EAA55735B240FF6369BEFE076791" box="[251,463,732,755]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="280">Oulema duftschmidi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="BAFD4D345735B240FE6769BEFD586791" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[511,656,732,755]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Oulema" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="melanopus">
<emphasis id="4F89EAA55735B240FE6769BEFD586791" box="[511,656,732,755]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="280">O. melanopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are well known European pests of cereals (
<taxonomicName id="BAFD4D345735B240FFE2699EFED86671" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[122,272,764,787]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Oulema" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="melanopus">
<emphasis id="4F89EAA55735B240FFE2699EFED86671" box="[122,272,764,787]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="280">O. melanopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
introduced also to North America) and can be frequently found on various 
<taxonomicName id="BAFD4D345735B240FFE9687EFF046651" authorityName="Barnhart" authorityYear="1895" baseAuthorityName="R.Br." box="[113,204,796,819]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="7" pageNumber="280" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Poaceae</taxonomicName>
. Host plants of 
<taxonomicName id="BAFD4D345735B240FEE4687EFD196651" authority="(Suffrian, 1847)" baseAuthorityName="Suffrian" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[380,721,796,819]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Lema" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufocyanea">
<emphasis id="4F89EAA55735B240FEE4687EFDDF6651" box="[380,535,796,819]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="280">O. rufocyanea</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="196C4B465735B240FDB0687EFD016651" author="SUFFRIAN E." box="[552,713,796,819]" pageId="7" pageNumber="280" pagination="98 - 102" refId="ref23088" refString="SUFFRIAN E. 1847: Zur Kritik einiger Kaferarten, nach Vergleich der Typen aus der Fabricius &quot; schen Sammlung. Entomologische Zeitung (Stettin) 8: 98 - 102." type="journal article" year="1847">Suffrian, 1847</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="BAFD4D345735B240FD46687EFC856651" authority="Bezděk &amp; Baselga, 2015" authorityName="Bezděk &amp; Baselga" authorityYear="2015" box="[734,845,796,819]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Oulema" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mauroi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="4F89EAA55735B240FD46687EFC856651" box="[734,845,796,819]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="280">O. mauroi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="54BA57DE5735B240FCCE687EFC666651" box="[854,942,796,819]" pageId="7" pageNumber="280" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, 
<taxonomicName id="BAFD4D345735B240FC23687EFBD16651" authority="Bezděk &amp; Baselga, 2015" authorityName="Bezděk &amp; Baselga" authorityYear="2015" box="[955,1049,796,819]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Oulema" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="4F89EAA55735B240FC23687EFBD16651" box="[955,1049,796,819]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="280">O. verae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="54BA57DE5735B240FBBA687EFF576631" pageId="7" pageNumber="280" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
are not known, but we presume also some 
<taxonomicName id="BAFD4D345735B240FDEC685EFD036631" authorityName="Barnhart" authorityYear="1895" baseAuthorityName="R.Br." box="[628,715,828,851]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="7" pageNumber="280" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Poaceae</taxonomicName>
species. 
<bibRefCitation id="196C4B465735B240FCB6685EFB896631" author="ROZNER I. &amp; ROZNER G." box="[814,1089,828,851]" pageId="7" pageNumber="280" pagination="111 - 131" refId="ref22727" refString="ROZNER I. &amp; ROZNER G. 2008: Data to the leaf-beetle fauna of Macedonia (Coleoptera, Chrysomelidae). Natura Somogyiensis 12: 111 - 131." type="journal article" year="2008">ROZNER &amp; ROZNER (2008)</bibRefCitation>
published 
<taxonomicName id="BAFD4D345735B240FF78683EFEA26611" box="[224,362,860,883]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lamiaceae" genus="Lamium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="7" pageNumber="280" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="4F89EAA55735B240FF78683EFEFF6611" box="[224,311,860,883]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="280">Lamium</emphasis>
spp.
</taxonomicName>
as host plant of 
<taxonomicName id="BAFD4D345735B240FD82683EFD7B6611" baseAuthorityName="Suffrian" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[538,691,860,883]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Lema" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufocyanea">
<emphasis id="4F89EAA55735B240FD82683EFD7B6611" box="[538,691,860,883]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="280">O. rufocyanea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry id="05EA76275735B240FD4E683EFC846611" box="[726,844,860,883]" name="Macedonia" pageId="7" pageNumber="280">Macedonia</collectingCountry>
but as other species of this group are associated with 
<taxonomicName id="BAFD4D345735B240FE22681EFDDC66F1" authorityName="Barnhart" authorityYear="1895" baseAuthorityName="R.Br." box="[442,532,892,915]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="7" pageNumber="280" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Poaceae</taxonomicName>
, the occurrence on 
<taxonomicName id="BAFD4D345735B240FD7E681EFCBA66F1" box="[742,882,892,915]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lamiaceae" genus="Lamium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="7" pageNumber="280" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="4F89EAA55735B240FD7E681EFCF566F1" box="[742,829,892,915]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="280">Lamium</emphasis>
spp.
</taxonomicName>
should be verified. Eastern Palaearctic 
<taxonomicName id="BAFD4D345735B240FEDC68FEFE6366D1" baseAuthorityName="Kuwayama" baseAuthorityYear="1931" box="[324,427,924,947]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Oulema" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oryzae">
<emphasis id="4F89EAA55735B240FEDC68FEFE6366D1" box="[324,427,924,947]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="280">O. oryzae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is associated with 
<taxonomicName id="BAFD4D345735B240FDED68FEFD3566D1" box="[629,765,924,947]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Oryza" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="7" pageNumber="280" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sativa">
<emphasis id="4F89EAA55735B240FDED68FEFD3566D1" box="[629,765,924,947]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="280">Oryza sativa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="35E7653C5735B24FFFE968DEFBAF6771" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="281" pageId="7" pageNumber="280" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="7D4236B75735B24FFFE968DEFBAF6771" blockId="7.[113,1089,220,1011]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1127,220,531]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="281" pageId="7" pageNumber="280">
<emphasis id="4F89EAA55735B240FFE968DEFE7266B1" bold="true" box="[113,442,955,979]" pageId="7" pageNumber="280">Comments on identification.</emphasis>
All European species are habitually extremely similar. As shown in 
<tableCitation id="307F030C5735B240FF4568BEFEE96691" box="[221,289,988,1011]" captionStart="Tab" captionStartId="7.[115,149,1072,1091]" captionTargetBox="[124,1065,1120,1588]" captionText="Tab. 1. Measurments of Oulema species." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/2982663F5735B240FFEB6F52FE066121" pageId="7" pageNumber="280" tableUuid="2982663F5735B240FFEB6F52FE066121">Tab. 1</tableCitation>
, ratios of the main measurements widely overlap and cannot be used for species separation – with the exception of the elytral length / elytral width ratio which helps to separate three units: 
<taxonomicName id="BAFD4D34573AB24FFE146B9EFDE06471" baseAuthorityName="Redtenbacher" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[396,552,252,275]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Oulema" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="duftschmidi">
<emphasis id="4F89EAA5573AB24FFE146B9EFDE06471" box="[396,552,252,275]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">O. duftschmidi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="BAFD4D34573AB24FFDC36B9EFD276471" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[603,751,252,275]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Oulema" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="melanopus">
<emphasis id="4F89EAA5573AB24FFDC36B9EFD276471" box="[603,751,252,275]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">O. melanopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, intermediate 
<taxonomicName id="BAFD4D34573AB24FFC1F6B9EFC2A6471" authority="Bezděk &amp; Baselga, 2015" authorityName="Bezděk &amp; Baselga" authorityYear="2015" box="[903,994,252,275]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Oulema" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="4F89EAA5573AB24FFC1F6B9EFC2A6471" box="[903,994,252,275]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">O. verae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="54BA57DE573AB24FFC706B9EFBF36471" box="[1000,1083,252,275]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and finally, 
<taxonomicName id="BAFD4D34573AB24FFF706A7EFE496451" baseAuthorityName="Suffrian" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[232,385,284,307]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Lema" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufocyanea">
<emphasis id="4F89EAA5573AB24FFF706A7EFE496451" box="[232,385,284,307]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">O. rufocyanea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="BAFD4D34573AB24FFE2E6A7EFDEB6451" authority="Bezděk &amp; Baselga, 2015" authorityName="Bezděk &amp; Baselga" authorityYear="2015" box="[438,547,284,307]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Oulema" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mauroi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="4F89EAA5573AB24FFE2E6A7EFDEB6451" box="[438,547,284,307]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">O. mauroi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="54BA57DE573AB24FFDB36A7EFDB66451" box="[555,638,284,307]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
The absolute measurements seem to be more useful, particularly body length, elytral length, elyral width and length of antennae, but also here the measurements partially overlap. The only really reliable characters to distinguish the species are the shape of the flagellum in males and the shape of the spermatheca in females, particularly the length and shape of the soft distal part of ductus spermathecae and its junction to bursa copulatrix. Surprisingly, the shape of spermatheca itself is almost invariable in this group and, on the contrary, the shape and number of coils of the well sclerotized proximal part of ductus spermathecae seem to be too variable and can only partially be used for identification.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
